The '''Nancy Grace Roman Space Telescope''' (shortened as the '''Roman Space Telescope''', '''Roman''', or '''RST''') is a [[NASA]] [[infrared]] [[space telescope]] that completed construction on November 25, 2025, and is scheduled to launch to a [[Lagrange point|Sun–Earth L<sub>2</sub> orbit]] on 30 August 2026.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://science.nasa.gov/blogs/roman/2026/06/03/hello-world-nasa-shares-new-home-for-roman-space-telescope-updates/  |title=Hello, World! NASA Shares New Home for Roman Space Telescope Updates |publisher=NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory |date=2026-06-03 |access-date=2026-06-03}}</ref>{{r|SN-20260108}}{{r|NASA20260422}}{{r|NASA20240521}} It is named after former NASA Chief of Astronomy [[Nancy Grace Roman]].<ref name="RomanSpaceTelescope" />

The Roman Space Telescope is based on an existing {{cvt|2.4|m|ft|adj=on}} wide [[field of view]] primary mirror [[2012 National Reconnaissance Office space telescope donation to NASA|donated by the National Reconnaissance Office]] and will carry two scientific instruments. The Wide-Field Instrument (WFI) is a 300.8-megapixel multi-band visible and [[Infrared|near-infrared]] camera, providing a sharpness of images comparable to that achieved by the [[Hubble Space Telescope]] over a 0.28 square degree field of view, 100 times larger than imaging cameras on the Hubble. The [[coronagraph|Coronagraph Instrument]] (CGI) is a high-contrast, small field of view camera and [[spectrometer]] covering visible and near-infrared wavelengths using novel starlight-suppression technology.

Stated objectives{{r|2015FinalReport}} include a search for [[Exoplanet|extra-solar planets]] using [[gravitational microlensing]],{{r|NRC}} along with probing the [[chronology of the universe]] and growth of cosmic structure, with the end goal of measuring the effects of [[dark energy]],{{r|RomanGSFC}} the consistency of [[general relativity]], and the [[Spacetime|curvature of spacetime]].

Roman was recommended in 2010 by the [[United States National Research Council]] [[Astronomy and Astrophysics Decadal Survey|Decadal Survey committee]] as the top priority for the next decade of astronomy. It was approved for development and launch on 17 February 2016.{{r|KDP-A}}

== Development of mission ==
[[File:WFIRST model.stl|thumb|upright=1.0|3D model of the telescope, as of 2020]]
The design of the Roman Space Telescope shares a heritage with various proposed designs for the [[Joint Dark Energy Mission]] (JDEM) between NASA and the [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] (DOE).

The original design, called WFIRST (Wide-Field Infrared Survey Telescope) Design Reference Mission 1, was studied in 2011–2012, featuring a {{cvt|1.3|m|ft|adj=on}} diameter unobstructed [[three-mirror anastigmat]] telescope.{{r|FinalReport}} It contained a single instrument, a visible to near-infrared imager/slitless [[prism spectrometer]].

In 2012, another possibility emerged: NASA could use a second-hand [[National Reconnaissance Office]] (NRO) telescope made by [[Harris Corporation]] to accomplish a mission like the one planned for WFIRST. [[2012 National Reconnaissance Office space telescope donation to NASA|NRO offered to donate two telescopes]], the same size as the [[Hubble Space Telescope]] but with a shorter focal length and hence a wider [[field of view]].{{r|TNYT}} This provided important political momentum to the project, even though the telescope represents only a modest fraction of the cost of the mission and the boundary conditions from the NRO design may push the total cost over that of a fresh design. This mission concept, called WFIRST-AFTA (Astrophysics Focused Telescope Assets), was matured by a scientific and technical team;{{r|AFTA}} this mission is now the only present NASA plan for the use of the NRO telescopes.{{r|SN-20130604}} The Roman baseline design includes a [[coronagraph]] to enable the [[Methods of detecting exoplanets#Direct imaging|direct imaging]] of [[exoplanet]]s.{{r|NASA20140430}}

Several implementations of WFIRST/Roman were studied. These included the Joint Dark Energy Mission-Omega configuration, an Interim Design Reference Mission featuring a {{cvt|1.3|m|ft}} telescope,{{r|Green2011}} Design Reference Mission 1{{r|DRM1}} with a 1.3 m telescope, Design Reference Mission 2{{r|DRM2}} with a {{cvt|1.1|m|ft}} telescope, and several iterations of the AFTA {{cvt|2.4|m|ft}} configuration. 

In the 2015 final report,<ref name="2015FinalReport" /> Roman was considered for both [[Geosynchronous orbit|geosynchronous]] orbit and for an orbit around the Sun-Earth [[Lagrange point]] L<sub>2</sub>. L<sub>2</sub> has disadvantages versus geosynchronous orbit in available data rate and propellant required, but advantages for improved observing constraints, better thermal stability, and more benign radiation environment. Some science cases (such as exoplanet [[Gravitational microlensing|microlensing]] parallax) are improved at L<sub>2</sub>, but the possibility of robotic servicing at either of the locations is currently unknown. By February 2016, it had been decided to use a [[halo orbit]] around L<sub>2</sub>.<ref name="KDP-A" />

The project is led by a team at NASA's [[Goddard Space Flight Center]] in [[Greenbelt, Maryland]]. On 30 November 2018, NASA announced it had awarded a contract for the telescope.{{r|Idaho State Journal}} This was for a part called the Optical Telescope Assembly (OTA), and runs to 2025.<ref name="Idaho State Journal"/> This is in conjunction with the Goddard Space Flight Center, for which the OTA is planned for delivery as part of this contract.<ref name="Idaho State Journal"/>

A February 2019 description of the mission's capabilities is available in a white paper issued by members of the Roman team.{{r|weinberg}}

During the [[2025 United States federal government shutdown|2025 federal government shutdown]], NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center began closing multiple buildings and consolidating equipment, which the agency describes as a pre-planned “strategic consolidation” not expected to impact missions.{{r|CNN Goddard shutdown closures}} A NASA spokesperson told CNN that work on the Nancy Grace Roman Space Telescope and the [[Dragonfly (Titan space probe)|Dragonfly]] mission would continue during the shutdown as excepted operations.<ref name="CNN Goddard shutdown closures"/>

According to Space.com, some employees at the center expressed concern that the manner and timing of the closures could disrupt work on those projects,{{r|dinner}} and CNN reported that an internal document compiled by Goddard staff cited potential impacts on specialized testing laboratories.<ref name="CNN Goddard shutdown closures"/>

