== Instruments ==
The telescope is to carry two instruments. Both were installed into the telescope in December 2024.{{r|NASA20241212}}
 [[File:Wide_Field_Instrument_Exploded_View.png|thumb|500x500px|Computer model, images, and labelled components of the Roman Space Telescope Wide Field Instrument. (a) Computer model of WFI. (b) Exploded view with labelled components. ACM: Alignment Compensation mechanism, which moves the focal plane assembly (FPA) into best focus both during commissioning and keeps it there over the lifetime of the mission. COBA: Cold Optical Baffle Assembly, which provides much of the stray light protection to the FPA. EWA: Element Wheel Assembly, which houses the eight science filters, prism and grism spectroscopy elements, and the "dark element", which aids in the calibration of the FPA. sRCS: simplified Relative Calibration Systems, which projects uniform light in two modes onto the focal plane to calibrate the FPA. (c) The completed instrument, wrapped in multilayer insulation. (d) Picture of the EWA prior to being covered during assembly. (e) A single filter prior to installation onto the wheel.<ref name=":0" />]]

;WFI: The Wide-Field Instrument (WFI) is the primary science instrument for the mission. It is a 300.8-[[megapixel]] camera, providing multiband imaging and spectroscopy from the visible to near-infrared (0.48 to 2.30&nbsp;μm).{{r|kruk}} Eight science filters, one wide band, and seven more narrow filters, provide high-quality images in subsets of the total spectral bandwidth of the instrument{{r|NASA20260130}}. It also carries both a high-dispersion [[grism]] and lower-dispersion [[Prism (optics)|prism]]{{r|eegholm}} assemblies for wide-field [[slitless spectroscopy]]. A "dark element" made out of [[spectralon]] can block out the light from space and reflect calibration light onto the detector. The eight filters, two spectroscopy elements, and dark element are all attached to an Element Wheel Assembly (EWA) that rotates one element at a time into the active position{{r|:0}}. This enables the scientists to choose which colors of light are needed for each mission{{r|schlieder}}, or switch between imaging and spectroscopy modes. A [[HgCdTe]]-based focal-plane array (FPA) captures a 0.28 square degree [[field of view]] with a resolution of 0.11 arcseconds. The detector array is composed of 18 H4RG-10 detectors provided by [[Teledyne Technologies|Teledyne]].{{r|NASA20180907}} The instrument carries on-board [[calibration]] capability to help the scientists discern the subtle changes in images from their dark matter mission compared to ordinary distortions of the optics or of the FPA{{r|NASA20260411}}. The FPA is attached to a set of hexapod [[Actuator|actuators]] that can reposition the focal plane into the best focus position based on analysis from the ground to ensure the captured images are always of high quality over the lifetime of the mission. WFI was completed and shipped to NASA in August 2024.{{r|NASA20240813}}

;CGI: The Coronagraph Instrument (CGI) is a high contrast [[coronagraph]] covering shorter wavelengths (575 nm to 825 nm) using dual deformable mirror starlight-suppression technology. It is intended to achieve a part-per-billion suppression of starlight to enable the detection and spectroscopy of planets with a visual separation of as little as 0.15&nbsp;arcseconds from their host stars.{{r|JPL20230222}} CGI is intended as a technology demonstrator for an exoplanet imaging instrument on a future large space-based observatory, such as the [[Habitable Worlds Observatory]] (HWO). 

